SIMPLE: stripe
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stripe
<hw>Stripe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OD. <ets>strijpe</ets>
a stripe, streak; akin to LG. <ets>stripe</ets>, D. <ets>streep</ets>,
Dan. <ets>stribe</ets>, G. <ets>strief</ets>, <ets>striefen</ets>, MHG.
<ets>striefen</ets> to glide, march.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A line, or
long, narrow division of anything of a different color or structure from
the ground; hence, any linear variation of color or structure; <as>as, a
<ex>stripe</ex>, or streak, of red on a green ground; a raised
<ex>stripe</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>A pattern produced by arranging
the warp threads in sets of alternating colors, or in sets presenting
some other contrast of appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A strip, or long, narrow piece attached to something
of a different color; <as>as, a red or blue <ex>stripe</ex> sewed upon a
garment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A stroke or blow made with a whip, rod, scourge, or
the like, such as usually leaves a mark.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forty <qex>stripes</qex> he may give him, and not exceed.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. xxv. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A long, narrow discoloration of the skin made by the
blow of a lash, rod, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cruelty marked him with inglorious <qex>stripes</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Color indicating a party or faction; hence,
distinguishing characteristic; sign; likeness; sort; <as>as, persons of
the same political <ex>stripe</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The chevron on
the coat of a noncommissioned officer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stars and Stripes</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Star</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></cd></cs> <-- To earn one's stripes, to acquire recognized
credentials by competent performance at a germane task. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stripe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stripe
<hw>Stripe</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Striped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Striping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make stripes
upon; to form with lines of different colors or textures; to variegate
with stripes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strike; to lash.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Striped</ent>⟦br⟧
